{{Infobox language |name=Boor |states=[[Chad]] |region=south |speakers=100 |date=1999 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Chadic languages|Chadic]] |fam3=[[East Chadic languages|East Chadic]] |fam4=[[East Chadic A languages|East Chadic A]] |fam5=[[Miltu languages|Miltu]] (A.1.2) |iso3=bvf |glotto=boor1242 |glottorefname=Boor }}
'''Boor''' (also known as Bwara, Damraw) is an endangered [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] language spoken in southern [[Chad]].<ref name=e18/> The language has less than 100 native speakers worldwide. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://endangeredlanguages.com/#/7/15.622/21.302/0/100000/0/low/mid/high/dormant/awakening/unknown|title=Endangered Languages Project|website=endangeredlanguages.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref>
Regions where the language is spoken include southern [[Chad]], the [[Bousso]] Subprefecture, [[Sarh]] Rural Subprefecture, and in and around the Dumraw village on the north bank of the [[Chari River]].
Due to the locations of the regions in which the language is spoken, native speakers of Boor commonly speak the [[Bagirmi language]] as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.ethnologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code=BVF|title=Ethnologue 14 report for language code:BVF|website=archive.ethnologue.com|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref>
