{{BLP sources|date=July 2011}} '''Emma Huismans''' (born July 10, 1947) is an [[Afrikaans]] writer, journalist, and activist born in the [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.let.leidenuniv.nl/Dutch/ModerneLetterkunde/Huismans1.html|title=Scriptie over Huismans|website=www.let.leidenuniv.nl|access-date=2018-05-06}}</ref> At the age of five her family moved to South Africa where she learned Afrikaans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biografieportaal.nl/author/emma-huismans/|title=Emma Huismans, auteur op Biografieportaal|website=Biografieportaal|language=nl-NL|access-date=2018-05-06}}</ref> She was later a reporter for [[The Crisis (newspaper)|Crisis News]]. Her efforts against [[apartheid]] were complicated by her being white, Afrikaans, and [[lesbian]]. This is dealt with in her premier work ''Berigte van weerstand.'' (English translation: ''Reports of resistance'')<ref name="Bertens1997">{{cite book|last=Bertens|first=Hans|title=International postmodernism: theory and literary practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n_Eqx2Gr1vUC&pg=PA487|accessdate=8 August 2011|year=1997|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|isbn=978-90-272-3445-2|pages=487–}}</ref> After that she did a few novels, but tended to do better in non-fiction. Her work is often deemed angry and frustrated with the difficulties of post-apartheid South Africa.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}
== Bibliography ==
*''Berigte van weerstand'' (1990) *''Requiem op ys'' (1992) *''Werken met werkelijkheid'' (1993) *''Sonate vir wraak'' (1994)
