{{Infobox language |name=Mikasuki |altname=Hitchiti-Mikasuki |states=[[United States]] |region=[[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], Southern [[Florida]] |ethnicity=[[Miccosukee]], [[Seminole]] |speakers=290 |date=2015 census |ref=e21 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Muskogean languages|Muskogean]] |fam2=Eastern |dia1=[[Hitchiti dialect|Hitchiti]] |iso3=mik |notice=IPA |glotto=mika1239 |glottorefname=Mikasuki }}
The '''Mikasuki language''' (also '''Miccosukee''', '''Mikisúkî''' or '''Hitchiti-Mikasuki''') is a [[Muskogean languages|Muskogean language]] spoken by around 500 people in southern [[Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news |title = Voices of the Everglades: Indian Culture |work = The News-Press |accessdate = 2014-03-28 |date = 2014-03-22 |url = http://www.news-press.com/article/20140322/ENT13/303230044/Voices-of-the-Everglades-Indian-culture?gcheck=1&nclick_check=1 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20140328034006/http://www.news-press.com/article/20140322/ENT13/303230044/Voices-of-the-Everglades-Indian-culture?gcheck=1&nclick_check=1 |archivedate = 2014-03-28 |df = }}</ref> Along with [[Muscogee language|Creek]], it is also known as Seminole. It is spoken by the [[Miccosukee]] tribe and many Florida [[Seminole]]. The extinct [[Hitchiti#Language|Hitchiti]] was a mutually-intelligible dialect.
The Seminole and Miccosukee were made up of mostly Creek members of the [[Creek Confederacy]], who had migrated to Florida under pressure from European-American encroachment. The Seminole formed by a process of [[ethnogenesis]] in the 18th century. American settlers began to enter Florida and came into conflict with the Seminole. The [[American Indian Wars|Seminole Wars of the 19th century]] greatly depleted the numbers of these tribes, specifically the [[Second Seminole War]]. The United States forcibly removed many Seminole to [[Indian Territory]] (now Oklahoma). The Seminole and Miccosukee had gradually moved into the center of Florida and the Everglades, from where they resisted defeat even in the Third Seminole War. The US gave up efforts against them.
In the 20th century, the Seminole and Miccosukee split apart, with the former moving onto reservations. The Miccosukee lived in communities that were affected by the early 20th-century construction of the [[Tamiami Trail]], which brought tourists into the Everglades.
The Miccosukee achieved federal recognition as a tribe in 1962. Both tribes have speakers of Mikasuki today.
As of 2002, the language was taught in the local school, which had "an area devoted to 'Miccosukee Language Arts'".<ref>{{Cite journal | issue = 56 | title = Elders Seek Way to Preserve Fading Language | journal = Canku Ota | accessdate = 2012-09-29 | date = 2002-03-09 | url = http://www.turtletrack.org/Issues02/Co03092002/CO_03092002_Miccosukee_Language.htm }}</ref>
As of 2011, the [[University of Florida]] Department of Anthropology is home to the Elling Eide Endowed Professorship in Miccosukee Language and Culture, for Native American languages of the southeastern United States.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Faculty Openings in the Anthropology Department | accessdate = 2012-09-29 | url = http://www.anthro.ufl.edu/faculty_search_09-10.shtml }}</ref>
Presentations in the language have been featured at the [[Florida Folk Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Traditional Seminole Song - Rev. Josie Billie | work = World Digital Library | accessdate = 2014-05-22 | url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/4053/#regions=north-america&languages=mik }}</ref>
==Phonology== {| class="wikitable" |- ! rowspan=2 | ! colspan="2" |Front ! colspan="2" |Central ! colspan="2" |Back |- ! &nbsp;Short&nbsp; ! Long ! &nbsp;Short&nbsp; ! &nbsp;Long&nbsp; ! &nbsp;Short ! &nbsp;Long |- ! align=center | &nbsp;[[High vowel|High]] (close)&nbsp; | align=center | '''i''' | align=center | '''iː''' | align=center | | align=center | | align=center | | align=center | |- ! align=center | &nbsp;[[Mid vowel|Mid]] (mid)&nbsp; | align=center | | align=center | | align=center | | align=center | | align=center | '''o''' | align=center | '''oː''' |- ! align=center | &nbsp;[[Low vowel|Low]] (open)&nbsp; | align=center | | align=center | | align=center | '''a''' | align=center | '''aː''' | align=center | | align=center | |}
There are three tones: high, low and falling. Vowel length is distinctive: ''eche'' [itʃi] ('mouth') vs ''eeche'' [iːtʃi]('deer'), ''ete'' [iti] ('eye') vs ''eete'' [iːti] ('fire').
{| class="IPA wikitable" ! colspan=2| ! [[labial consonant|Labial]] ! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! [[glottal consonant|Glottal]] |-align=center ! rowspan=2|[[Stop consonant|Stop]] !<small>voiceless</small> | p | t | k | |-align=center !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small> | b | | | |-align=center ! colspan=2|[[Affricate consonant|Affricative]] | | tʃ | | |-align=center ! colspan=2|[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | ɸ | ɬ | ʃ | |-align=center ! colspan=2|[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] | m | n | | |-align=center ! colspan=2|[[Sonorant consonant|Resonant]] | w | l | j | h |}
These phonemes are based on Sylvia Boynton's Outline of Mikasuki Grammar.<ref>Boynton, S. S. (1982). MIKASUKI GRAMMAR IN OUTLINE (INDIANS; FLORIDA). (Order No. 8302210, University of Florida). ProQuest Dissertations and Theses, 203-203 p. Retrieved from http://search.proquest.com/docview/303232611</ref>
==Grammar== Nouns are marked with suffixes for various functions, some examples: {| class="wikitable" |'''Suffix''' |'''Function''' |'''Example''' |'''Meaning''' |- | | |embaache |''battery'' |- |ot |subject marker |embaachot hampeepom |''the battery has gone bad'' |- |on |object marker |embaachon aklomle |''I need a battery'' |- |ee |question marker |embachee cheméèło? |''do you have a battery?'' |- |}
Free pronouns exist (''aane'' "I", ''chehne'' "you", ''pohne'' "we") but are rarely used. Verb suffixes are the usual way of marking person.
==Alphabet== Mikasuki is written using the Latin alphabet. The vowels are pronounced as follows: {| class="wikitable" |'''Letter''' |'''Sound''' |- |a, aa |{{IPA|a}}, {{IPA|aː}} |- |<u>a</u>, <u>aa</u> |{{IPA|ã}}, {{IPA|ãː}} |- |e, ee |{{IPA|i}}, {{IPA|iː}} |- |<u>e</u>, <u>ee</u> |{{IPA|ĩː}}, {{IPA|ĩː}} |- |o, oo |{{IPA|o}}, {{IPA|oː}} |- |<u>o</u>, <u>oo</u> |{{IPA|õ}}; {{IPA|õː}} |- |ay |{{IPA|ai}} |- |ao |{{IPA|ao}} |- |} The consonants are: {| class="wikitable" |'''Letter''' |'''Sound''' |- |b |{{IPA|b}} |- |ch |{{IPA|t͡ʃ}} |- |f |{{IPA|ɸ}} |- |h |{{IPA|h}} |- |k |{{IPA|k}} |- |l |{{IPA|l}} |- |ł |{{IPA|ɬ}} |- |m |{{IPA|m}} |- |n |{{IPA|n}} |- |ng |{{IPA|ŋ}} |- |p |{{IPA|p}} |- |sh |{{IPA|ʃ}} |- |t |{{IPA|t}} |- |w |{{IPA|w}} |- |y |{{IPA|j}} |}
High tone is indicated with an acute accent (´), low tone with a grave accent (`), and falling tone with an acute accent followed by a grave accent. A long vowel with falling tone is represented by two accented vowel letters (áà). When the vowel is short, the grave accent is placed over the next consonant (áǹ): {| class="wikitable" |High Tone |Low Tone |Falling Tone |- |á, áa |à, àa |áǹ, áà |- |} An [[Svarabhakti|epenthetic]] [ə] vowel appears in kl, kw and kn clusters in careful speech.
